<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-383-750  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 383 750.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  April 23 1990 n587 p10(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>X-ray lithography gains momentum.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Santo, Brian.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The National X-Ray Lithography Program, funded primarily by theDefense Advanced Research Projects Agency, is seeing a flurry ofactivity as the US effort to develop the technology increases inresponse to similar programs in Japan, France, and Germany, whichare already ahead of US efforts.andP;  Recent developments includecirculation by the Energy Department of an RFP for two moresynchrotrons; Grumman's reiteration of its intention to become asupplier of turnkey X-ray lithographic systems; installation of alow-energy synchrotron scheduled to begin at Brookhaven NationalLaboratory; a contract between IBM and Hampshire Instruments tomake X-ray masks and expose test wafers with half-microncircuitry; and the joint support of IBM, Grumman, and Etec for thedevelopment of E-beam technology for X-ray masks.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     X-RaysStereolithographyTechnologyUnited States. Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>